'''Tōchi no Miagata Nimasu Shrine''' (とおちのみあがたにますじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Kashihara|Q496319|WD=Q496319|1=Kashihara, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|WD=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}. The ''Great Yamato Province Tax Register'' of {{ill|lt=730|Q23563|WD=Q23563|1=730}} ({{ill|lt=Tenpyō|Q1199879|WD=Q1199879|1=Tenpyō}} 3; {{ill|lt=Shōsōin documents|Q11545362|WD=Q11545362|1=Shōsōin Documents}}) records “Tōichi Mikata Kōbe,” showing it is an ancient shrine continuing from before the {{ill|lt=Nara period|Q189178|WD=Q189178|1=Nara period}}. It is a {{ill|lt=shikinaisha great shrine|Q134917288|WD=Q134917288|1=Shikinai Taisha}}, and its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|WD=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
*Main deity: {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Toyouke Ōkami|1=UNKNOWN}}
*Associated deity: {{ill|UNKNOWN|WD=Q11059454|lt=Ichikishimahime-no-Mikoto|1=Ichikishima-hime}}
**According to shrine tradition, the deity is '''{{ill|lt=Ōme|Q97496325|WD=Q97496325|lt=Ōme|1=Toichi no Agatanushi Ōme}}''', ancestor of the Tōichi Agatanushi seen in the ''{{ill|lt=Kōrei Tennō-ki|Q313041|WD=Q313041|1=Emperor Kōrei}}''. Isasaka-hime, daughter of Tōichi Agatanushi Isasakahiko, was {{ill|lt=Emperor Kōan|Q312821|WD=Q312821|1=Emperor Kōan}}’s {{ill|lt=empress|Q7723211|WD=Q7723211|1=Empress consort}}; and {{ill|lt=Hosohime-no-Mikoto|Q11605816|WD=Q11605816|1=Kuwashi-hime}}, daughter of Ōme, was Empress of Emperor Kōrei.

=== History ===
The founding date is unknown, but it is an ancient shrine listed in the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}''. Since ancient times it was {{ill|lt=Imperial Household|Q909452|WD=Q909452|1=Imperial House of Japan}} {{ill|lt=Imperial property|Q11581043|WD=Q11581043|lt=land|1=imperial property}}, and worshiped the spirit of sacred vegetable gardens used to cultivate {{ill|lt=vegetables|Q952624|WD=Q952624|1=Olericulture}} offered to the {{ill|lt=emperor|Q208233|WD=Q208233|1=Emperor of Japan}}. Together with Takachi, Katsuraki, Tōichi, Shiki, Yamabe, and Sofu, it was one of the “{{ill|lt=Six Agata of Yamato|Q55521849|WD=Q55521849|lt=Six Mikata Shrines of Yamato Province|1=The Six Prefectures of Wa}},” deeply revered by the imperial court. On {{ill|lt=January 27 (lunar)|Q839032|WD=Q839032|lt=January 27|1=January 27 (Lunisolar)}}, {{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}} ({{ill|lt=Ten'an|Q1075611|WD=Q1075611|1=Ten'an}} 3), its {{ill|lt=court rank for shrines|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}} rose to {{ill|lt=Junior Fifth Upper|Q11071125|WD=Q11071125|1=Junior Fifth Rank}} and shrine households were allotted. In the reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Daigo|Q329753|WD=Q329753|1=Emperor Daigo}}, under the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Engi system|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, it was listed as a {{ill|lt=great shrine|Q11438310|WD=Q11438310|1=Taisha (shrine)}} and received official offerings at the Kinen, Tsukinami, and Niiname rites. In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}} it was also called “Jūsansho (Jūsasho) Daimyōjin,” but was identified with the Engishiki “Tōichi Mikata-ni-masu Shrine.”

